Les Berges de Seine is a 3 km long dedicated pedestrian and cycling path that is excellent go exercise or commute along. On the western edge is  Pont Royal and on the eastern edge is Musee Quay Branly. The City of Paris stages temporary exhibits here that focus on physical activity, social life and the environment. There are also a number of restaurants to have a drink or a light bite. It's a lovely space to find yourself whiling away an afternoon.

The banks of the Seine (Berges de Seine) are a must-visit walk in Paris, where you can appreciate the evening life of the city. When everyone leaves work, on a summer and spring afternoon (in winter the cold keeps you away), you can see a lot of Parisians and tourists walking and doing recreational activities. But the majority organize to have a snack and drink (especially the latter) in the company of friends and family. The truth is that it is a spectacle that cannot be appreciated by going in winter, Paris is better in spring, summer and autumn. From experience, my first trip was in a harsh winter, I had a great time, but when I went in July (first week) the heat was not so terrible and you can appreciate all the beauty of its gardens and the mythical Seine.

A wonderful walk around Paris. On the Embankment there are many viewing platforms for attractions, cafes, restaurants on the water, piers for pleasure boats. There are rope paths on the ancient walls of the embankment, which both children and adults enjoy climbing.

Really a magnificent place if you remove the smells, in summer by bike it is very attractive especially as there are restaurants water points and different Ephemeral exhibitions each time with young artists.

I don't know if it's good for cars but the fact that the banks have become pedestrianized is great for pedestrians of all kinds. Go for a walk. Stroll, feel the soul of Paris. From street art in cafes along the Seine to Sunday afternoon dancing along the banks. Get lost on the Parisian bridges, wander among runners, children, bikes, tourists, walkers. Observe people admiring the monuments. In short, don't pass through Paris without going there. Day or night it is a must.
From the Seine there is a completely different view of the whole of Paris and its magical places. In the winter months, I recommend not to underestimate the cold on the water and dress properly.
